# Walkthrough: Issue #4 Phase 1 (Message -> LLM -> Reply)

This walkthrough documents the completion of the core chat loop functionality for the Akasa chatbot.

## What was Changed

1. **Service Layer Architecture**:
   - Implemented [app/services/llm_service.py](file:///Users/oatrice/Software-projects/Akasa/app/services/llm_service.py) to handle interactions with the OpenRouter API.
   - Implemented [app/services/telegram_service.py](file:///Users/oatrice/Software-projects/Akasa/app/services/telegram_service.py) to handle sending messages back to users via the Telegram Bot API.
   - Implemented [app/services/chat_service.py](file:///Users/oatrice/Software-projects/Akasa/app/services/chat_service.py) to act as the main orchestrator, receiving the message text, sending it to the LLM, and returning the reply to the user.

2. **Webhook Update**:
   - Modified [app/routers/telegram.py](file:///Users/oatrice/Software-projects/Akasa/app/routers/telegram.py)'s [telegram_webhook](file:///Users/oatrice/Software-projects/Akasa/app/routers/telegram.py#38-51) endpoint to use FastAPI's `BackgroundTasks`.
   - The webhook now immediately responds to Telegram with `200 OK` and passes the actual processing to `chat_service.handle_chat_message` in the background.

## Verification

The feature was implemented using **Test-Driven Development (TDD)**:

1. **Unit Tests (Green)**: 
   - Wrote failing `pytest` mocks for [test_llm_service.py](file:///Users/oatrice/Software-projects/Akasa/tests/services/test_llm_service.py), [test_telegram_service.py](file:///Users/oatrice/Software-projects/Akasa/tests/services/test_telegram_service.py), [test_chat_service.py](file:///Users/oatrice/Software-projects/Akasa/tests/services/test_chat_service.py), and [test_telegram.py](file:///Users/oatrice/Software-projects/Akasa/tests/routers/test_telegram.py). 
   - Implemented the code until all 8 unit tests passed successfully.
2. **Manual Test (Webhook Simulation)**: 
   - Created and ran a [test_webhook.sh](file:///Users/oatrice/Software-projects/Akasa/test_webhook.sh) script using `curl` to send a simulated Telegram JSON payload to the locally running server (`http://127.0.0.1:8000/api/v1/telegram/webhook`).
   - The webhook successfully verified the secret token and returned `{"status": "ok"}` while handing off the payload to the background task.
